    "# *Resumen artículo: Python has brought computer programming to a vast new audience.*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "Guido van Rossum is a Dutch computer scientist who devised Python in December 1989. He had rally simple principles such as being easy to read, it should let users create their own packages of special-purpose coding modules and also he wanted it to have a short, unique and kind of mysterious name. That is how Python was created, and now after 30 years, Guido van Rossum resembles a technological version of the Monty Python. In the las year, Python has been one of the most \"Googled\" concepts in America.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The language’s popularity has been increasing among professional developers, nearly 40% of whom use it, and at least 25% wishing to do it. Studies show that the biggest increase in demand comes from those who wish to learn Python.\n",
    "As we all now, Python is not a perfect language and there are many other options that can give the user a great experience and more control over what is happening within a computer’s processor such as C, C++, Java, JavaScript and more with different features and purposes, but Python has a simple syntax which makes that easy to learn and teach, plus many other features that makes it a good general-purpose language. \n",
    "\n",
    "It was proposed that one of the best solutions for semi-educated tinkerers is to educate them correctly in the language’s arcana. In 2014, Python was already one of the most popular languages at American Universities, even though it is generally limited for some studies such as science, technology, mathematics and engineering. Another solution a little bit more radical is to offer computer science to everyone since primary education, and the percentage of schools teaching these lessons has increase since 2013.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this moment is uncertain how much longer will Python rise, but with other languages example we can guess in some year Python will be left in the background. It is true that Mr. Van Rossum did something memorable, but no computing language can always be truly general purpose, it will necessarily remain importer some type of specialization."
